<DOC><DOCNO> AP891124-0081 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-89 1212EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vietnam-Refugees     11-24 0188</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Vietnam-Refugees,0193</SECOND><HEAD>U.N. Demands Inquiry Into Boat People Allegation</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United Nations' refugee agency Fridaycalled on Hong Kong to investigate allegations that undue force wasused when moving Vietnamese boat people between detention centers.   The office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees hasprotested the circumstances surrounding the Oct. 31 move of 48Vietnamese, who are among the tens of thousands of boat peopleseeking asylum in the British colony.   Some of the moved Vietnamese reportedly claimed that securityforces used martial arts to immobilize them during the move from adetention center to Phoenix House, a holding center for Vietnamesewho may be forcibly returned to their Communist homeland.   The government denies that undue force was used.   More than 50,000 Vietnamese who fled to Hong Kong by boat arelanguishing in squalid camps throughout the territory. Most mustprove they fled political persecution to qualify for refugee statusor face mandatory repatriation.   Tens of thousands of Vietnamese are expected to be deniedrefugee status. Tension in the camps has increased recently withthe possibility of a program of forced repatriation.</TEXT></DOC>